{"id":"cond-mat/0602619","submitter":"Marc-Andr\\'e Dupertuis","authors":"Monique Combescot and Marc-Andr\\'e Dupertuis","title":"The carrier ''antibinding'' in quantum dots: a charge separation effect","comments":"9 pages, no figures, accepted for publication in European Journal of\n  Physics B","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1140/epjb/e2006-00151-8","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":null,"abstract":"  We show that the carrier ''antibinding'' observed recently in semiconductor\nquantum dots, i.e., the fact that the ground state energy of two electron-hole\npairs goes above twice the ground-state energy of one pair, can entirely be\nassigned to a charge separation effect, whatever its origin. In the absence of\nexternal electric field, this charge separation comes from different\n''spreading-out'' of the electron and hole wavefunctions linked to the finite\nheight of the barriers. When the dot size shrinks, the two-pair energy always\nstays below when the barriers are infinite. On the opposite, because barriers\nare less efficient for small dots, the energy of two-pairs in a dot with finite\nbarriers, ends by behaving like the one in bulk, i.e., by going above twice the\none-pair energy when the pairs get too close. For a full understanding of this\n''antibinding'' effect, we have also reconsidered the case of one pair plus one\ncarrier. We find that, while the carriers just have to spread out of the dot\ndifferently for the ''antibinding'' of two-pairs to appear, this\n''antibinding'' for one pair plus one carrier only appears if this carrier is\nthe one which spreads out the less. In addition a remarkable sum rule exists\nbetween the \"binding energies\" of two pairs and of one pair plus one carrier.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 27 Feb 2006 09:50:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-11"}
